  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Edict Bestowing Gifts Upon An'pyeong Baron Kyong
  author: Choe Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    An edict to the Baron:

    The Book of Changes speaks of Emperor Yi's daughter going forth in marriage, and the Book of Poetry contains verses on the King's daughter taking her place as bride. Yet these gifts serve not merely to display the splendor of carriage and robes, but to deepen the affection between kin.

    You have inherited the house of the noble Hung, and the imperial clan has praised your virtue. With loyalty and filial piety rooted in your heart, you received the guidance of righteous instruction from your youth. Through the study of Poetry and History, your refined talents grow daily. Early did you receive the honor of enfeoffment, and now you have achieved this auspicious marriage in its proper season. Thus do We bestow these gifts abundantly, that Our regard for you may be known.

    As lute and zither harmonize together, so shall your household be filled with joy, and as branch and root flourish side by side, so shall you become the glory of the realm. Though blessed with wealth and honor, remain humble and without pride. Guard yourself with modesty, preserve your union unto old age, and maintain a name of virtue.

    We therefore dispatch Official Kim Chongsu to present to you robes and girdles, vessels of gold and silver, bolts of fine cloth, precious goods, saddle-horses, and all such items as detailed in the accompanying record.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to Emperor Yi and the King's daughter alludes to auspicious precedents from classical texts, suggesting this marriage is favorable and well-ordained.
    - The mention of 'lute and zither' is a traditional metaphor for marital harmony in East Asian poetry.
